  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT260-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">avar varaviṟku nimittam āyiṉa kaṇṭu āṟṟāḷākiya talaimakaṭkut tōḻi
          colliyatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">The confidante speaking to HER who didn't have strength
          [anymore], upon seeing the signs for his coming. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT260">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l>kuruku miruvicum pivarum putalum</l>
          <l>varivaṇ ṭūta vāynekiḻn taṉavē</l>
          <l>curivaḷaip polinta tōḷuñ ceṟṟum</l>
          <l>varuvarkol vāḻi tōḻi poruvār</l>
          <l>maṇṇeṭut tuṇṇu maṇṇal yāṉai</l>
          <l>vaṇṭērt toṇṭaiyar vaḻaiyama laṭukkattuk</l>
          <l>kaṉṟi lōrā vilaṅkiya</l>
          <l>puṉṟā ḷōmaiya curaṉiṟan tōrē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Herons are climbing the dark sky, and <note place="foot">The double marking <term xml:lang="ta">kuruk'um – putal-um</term> makes clear that both sentences have to be
            read as coordinate, in spite of the strangely incompatible verb forms <term xml:lang="ta">ivarum</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">nekiḻtaṉavē</term> . This is a
            passage to argue for the advantages of an aspectual system: ivarum expresses the
            continuous event (ever more herons, or, every now and then another heron), while <term xml:lang="ta">nekiḻtaṉa</term> is not past tense, but either a perfective or a kind
            of aorist: they have opened, and now they are open.</note> shrubs</l>
          <l>have opened [their blossom] mouths</l>
          <l rend="indent6">so that striped bees fill themselves [with pollen]. <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">ūta</term> here is ambiguous. The verb can either refer to blowing
            as a sound or to being inflated by eating (cf. note on KT 211.5). Since here (unlike in
            the two KT parallels 211.5 and 239.4) the object is missing (the thing on which the bees
            are feeding), <term xml:lang="ta">ūta</term> might also refer to their humming.</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent">Even though [my] upper arms glittering with winding bangles</l>
          <l rend="indent9">have resisted, <note place="foot">T.V.G. reads also line 3 as an
            independent sentence ("Also [your] upper arms, glittering with curved bangles, are
            resisting.") and takes the first three lines as good omens for HIS imminent arrival (the <term xml:lang="ta">nimittam</term> , "signs", the confidante of the <term xml:lang="ta">
            kiḷavi</term> sees). Therefore he has to explain the kol of <term xml:lang="ta">
            varuvar-kol</term> as an expletive and read an assurance on the part of the confidante
            that HE will come now.</note>
          </l>
          <l>will he come, oh friend,</l>
          <l>he who traversed the desert of low-based Ōmai trees,</l>
          <l rend="indent">across which lies a single cow without calf</l>
          <l rend="indent2">from the mountainside thick with Vaḻai trees,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">of the Toṇṭaiyar with many chariots [and] majestic elephants, </l>
          <l>who take over the land of [enemy] fighters? <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">poruvār maṇ eṭuttu uṇṇum: Srin</term> . analyses this strange
            expression as a Sanskritism, namely as a transliteration of <term xml:lang="ta">bhū-bhuj</term>
            , taking enemies' land, apparently in accordance with Cam’s gloss. This would free us
            from having to assume that elephants eat earth, or even worse, buried warriors.</note>
          </l>

          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="7b" resp="#TVG">
            <l>which prevented a calfless cow [from going further]<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vilaṅkiya</term> is difficult here. Is the point that the trees are
              so small the cow has to lie along several of them in order to get some shade? T.V.G.
              prefers to take it as a metaphor: the Ōmai trees, which give at least a little shade,
              stopped the cow on her way.</note>
            </l>
          </lg>

        </lg>
      </div>
